{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-js","path":"/module2","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"courseId":"RLeapFROGS"}},"markdownRemark":{"htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"0","title":"Opening Rstudio","type":"slides"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"slides","properties":{"source":"chapter2_01_introduction_to_Rstudio"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"1","title":"The R console"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The R console can be used to evaluate any R code."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This includes functioning as a simple calculator."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_01"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can see that R is a pretty good calculator. All of the functionality of a scientific calculator is built in to base R."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"2","title":"R classes"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"R is a high-level language. In order to performcomplex tasks with little code, R makes lots of assumptions. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This includes automated classification of inputs"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_02"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"These examples will give you some starting assumptions. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Typing an unquoted number into the console will give a ‘numeric’ classification, while quoted numbers become ‘characters’. ‘integer’ objects are assigned explicity."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Read more about "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/base/html/class.html"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"classes"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"3","title":"value assignment"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Assignment in R is performed primarily with the following operator ”<-”, wherein an object is assigned a value such as ‘a <- 1’"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_03"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"After we assigned letters to the objects ‘a’, ‘b’, and ‘c’, the function ‘c()’ combined them to form a vector of length 3."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Read more about "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-patched/library/base/html/assignOps.html"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"assignment in R"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"3.1","title":"an R project","type":"slides"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now that we’ve explored some of the basics from the console, let’s create an R project to house our work"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"slides","properties":{"source":"chapter5_04_R_project"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"4","title":"R functions"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you have successfully initiated a new R project, you can add your first R script to the project to house the code you’ll be writing."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can decide for yourself how many files to create and how to separate topics. Hopefully these scripts can serve as notes for you to reflect on later."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"R is a functional programming languange. Objects are created and altered by applying functions."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Functions accept a set of paramters, often called arguments."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Here’s a first look at a simple function:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_04"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Writing functions is simple, but requires a specific syntax."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"5","title":"R functions (cont)"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s expand our function by adding a new parameter."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Suppose were are tring to alphabetize our strings, so we sometimes use this new function to return the place in the alphabet of the first letter of our string."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We can add a new parameter, ‘place’, which takes a boolean (TRUE/FALSE) value."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_05"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Notice that our new parameter triggers an ‘if’ switch, which in turn determines the type of output returned by the function."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"‘letters’ is a built-in variable, a vector of the 26 letters of the alphabet. ‘tolower()’ is a function that takes letters and returns the lower-case equivalent."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"comparing ‘letters’ with the first letter of the input ‘string’ using the ’==’ operator returns a set of 26 boolean values"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"the function ‘which()’ tells us which of the 26 boolean values are ‘TRUE’, and as ‘z’ is the 26th letter of the alphabet, we get 26"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If we do not provide the ‘place’ argument, the default value of ‘FALSE’ is used, so we get the letter, ‘z’ in this case"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Read more about "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://r4ds.had.co.nz/functions.html"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"functions"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"17","title":"A Data Frame"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Data tables, which you may be accustomed to using as Excel spredsheets, are called data frames in R."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Data frames store data in two dimensions with column names and optional row names. mtcars is a data frame distributed with the basic R installation."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A popular package for manipulating data frames is dplyr."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"02_17"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"See more "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"data frame manipulation techniques from dpylr"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"id":2,"title":"Module 2: First R project","description":"This module will guide you through development of your first R project","next":"/module3","prev":"/module1"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/module2"}},"staticQueryHashes":["1029480139","1771538597","3063084251","4240431937"]}